secting efforts to computerize mapmaking, standardize geographic names, and respond to public concern over ethnically offensive appellations. Interweaving cartographic history with tales of politics and power, celebrated geographer Mark Monmonier locates his story within the past and present struggles of mapmakers to create an orderly process for naming that avoids confusion, preserves history, and serves different political aims. Anchored by a diverse selection of naming controversies—in the United States, Canada, Cyprus, Israel, Palestine, and Antarctica; on the ocean floor and the surface of the moon; and in other parts of our solar system—From Squaw Tit to Whorehouse Meadow richly reveals the map’s role as a mediated portrait of the cultural landscape. And unlike other books that consider place names, this is the first to reflect on both the real cartographic and political imbroglios they engender. From Squaw Tit to Whorehouse Meadow is Mark Monmonier at his finest: a learned analysis of a timely and controversial subject rendered accessible—and even entertaining—to the general reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnglais (Langue)xMots obscènes. 0aAnglais (Langue)xÉtymologiexNoms. 0aEnglish languagexEtymologyxNames. 0aEnglish languagexObscene words. 0aMots obscènesxUnited States. 0aNames, GeographicalxEtymologyxUnited States. 0aNames, GeographicalxEtymology. 0aNoms géographiquesxÉtymologiexÉtats-Unis. 0aNoms géographiquesxÉtymologie. 0aToponymie. 0aToponymy. 0aWords, Obscene. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amapmaking, place names, vulgarity, derogatory, racial slurs, squaw tit, nevada, outhouse draw, utah, mollys nipple, alaska, brassiere hills, political correctness, sanctions, jap valley, scatalogy, race, ethnicity, cartography, geography, standardization, history, politic